
╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  MISSION: LOG ANALYSIS                                                    ║
║  SKILL: grep (pattern searching)                                          ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

OBJECTIVE:
The system logs contain thousands of entries. Something triggered a cascade
of failures, but finding it manually would take hours. Use grep to search
for patterns and identify the root cause.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASK: Find the Source of the Critical Failure
─────────────────────────────────────────────
The logs contain entries marked as INFO, WARNING, ERROR, and CRITICAL.

1. First, find how many CRITICAL errors exist across all log files.
2. Then, identify which SYSTEM caused the first CRITICAL failure.

The answer is a system name (one word, like "NAVIGATION" or "PROPULSION").

When you find the system name, run:
    ./verify <system_name>

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

USEFUL COMMANDS:
    grep "CRITICAL" *.log              Search all log files for CRITICAL
    grep -c "CRITICAL" *.log           Count CRITICAL entries per file
    grep -n "CRITICAL" system.log      Show line numbers of matches
    grep "CRITICAL" *.log | head -5    Show first 5 matches

LOG FILES:
    system.log      - Main system log
    power.log       - Power management log
    network.log     - Network systems log
    sensors.log     - Sensor array log

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

